                                                                 
                                                                           Synapse Annual Fest Database

1. Introduction
1.1 Purpose
Synapse is an annual fest of DA-IICT which includes thousands of attendees, various events, artists, accommodations, etc.
It becomes difficult to keep track of data like, when and where will this event take place? How many people will be attending this event?
Are there any more rooms available for accommodation? How many, which artist(s) will be present in a particular event, their contact details. 
What are the different types of tickets available? Platinum, Golden, silver (varying number of events included), 
or tickets including only 1 particular event,  and their availability.
 
Hence it becomes essential to maintain a database for synapse.
>        It eliminates manual data handling.
>        Provide real-time monitoring of event schedules, venues and ticket status.
>        Enable rapid generation of reports for Synapse committee.
>        It avoids human errors, manual ticketing which often leads to errors.
>        Quick updates, last minute changes in venues or timing require rapid actions, which cannot be achieved by humans.


1.2 Intended audience
Database will be accessed by synapse committee members, administration, volunteers and IT staff.
->  Suppose they want to arrange food, water or beverages  for a particular event, how much of these should they arrange? 
They can look for numbers of tickets sold for this particular event to get an idea of size of audience.
Once they have the idea of size of audience, they can also arrange for seating arrangement.
-> Suppose an artist is running late for an event, committee members can find his contact details quickly from the database and contact him for updates.
->  IT staff: tasked with system deployment, trouble shooting and ongoing maintenance. They need operational  instructions, back up plans and support requirements.


1.3 Product scope
The System will provide the committee with tools
to:
Create and manage events (music, dance, drama, tech, art, formal events etc.)
Manage venues and schedule events to avoid clashes
Register artists/performers and link them to events
Support multiple ticket types and pass models (single-event, event-package, Platinum/Gold passes that cover multiple or all events)
Record ticket sales details, buyer’s details. 
Manage attendee information and accommodation bookings
Maintain records for food vendors and sponsor details
Generate standard reports (tickets sold per-event, revenue, artist schedule, capacity utilization)
Out of scope (for initial release):
Full integration with live payment gateway 
Mobile native app. 


1.4 Description 
Synapse is the flagship techno-cultural festival of DAU (Dhirubhai Ambani University), held annually in Gandhinagar, Gujarat. 
It spans four electrifying days, typically in February, and brings together a vibrant fusion of technology, culture, arts, and entertainment.
Celebrating the intersection of creativity and innovation, Synapse features an extensive lineup—ranging from pro-nights with 
celebrated artists to competitions across music, dance, drama, fashion, literature, photography, eSports, coding, and more. 
Such diversity makes it one of Gujarat’s most prominent college fests.
Highlights include staging major pro-nights featuring renowned performers such as Salim-Sulaiman, Amit Trivedi, Antara Mitra,
and DJ acts like Teri Miko, each drawing huge crowds and setting the fest's energy high.
The fest is designed to engage students, artists, technophiles, and cultural enthusiasts in an enriching mix of experiences—competitions 
like “Battle of Bands”, “Rampage” (fashion show), “Footloose” (contemporary dance), “Stage Play”, and “Cynosure” (main celebrity night);
tech challenges like “Tech Hunt”, “Battledrome” (eSports), “Math-ify”; literary competitions such as “Shailee” (poetry & creative writing),
“Anweshan” (research papers), “Samwaad” (parliamentary debate); creative zones like “CosCon” (cosplay), “Conceive” (photography),
plus genre-spanning showcases in traditional dance, mime, street play (“Nukkad Natak”), and solo performances (“Mono Acte”).
Beyond entertainment, Synapse is a student-owned endeavor that empowers hundreds of volunteers and committee members across multiple 
teams—event management, hospitality, PR, design, sponsorship, finance, and web—each coordinating tasks, publicity, sponsorship outreach,
and infrastructure to bring the fest to life.
The architecture of the fest is intentional: performances coexist with competitions, cultural expressions meet technological innovation, 
and student leadership combines with professional coordination—all under one dynamic roof.
This complex orchestration needs a robust backend system to manage events, artists, ticketing, vendors, accommodation, schedules, sponsors, and reporting.
